---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Learn Xeto — xeto.dev">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">What is Xeto?</h1>

  <div class="mt-6 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-ink-soft">
    <p>
      <strong class="text-ink">Xeto</strong> ("extensible explicitly typed
      objects") is a language for defining typed data specifications. A Xeto
      <em>spec</em> describes the shape of data — its slots, types, constraints,
      and documentation — and a Xeto <em>library</em> packages related specs
      together with versioning and dependencies.
    </p>
    <p>
      Think of it like a type system for the data layer: instead of every
      project inventing its own JSON conventions, domains share libraries of
      well-defined types that tooling can validate against, generate from, and
      document automatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      Xeto grew out of
      <a
        href="https://project-haystack.org"
        class="text-brand underline decoration-brand-soft underline-offset-2"
        >Project Haystack</a
      >
      and the smart-buildings world, where it types everything from HVAC points
      to ASHRAE control sequences — but the language itself is domain-neutral.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mt-12 text-xl font-semibold">A taste of the language</h2>
  <pre
    class="mt-4 max-w-3xl overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-line bg-paper-soft p-5 text-sm"><code>// A spec describes the shape of data: a Book has a
// title (text), an author (text), and a page count (number).
// The "?" marks rating as optional.
Book: Dict &#123;
  title: Str
  author: Str
  pages: Int
  rating: Int?
&#125;

// This is data — a real book. Because it says it's a Book,
// tools can check it has everything a Book requires.
@dune: Book &#123;title: "Dune", author: "Frank Herbert", pages: 412&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2 class="mt-12 text-xl font-semibold">Why a spec language?</h2>
  <div class="mt-4 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-ink-soft">
    <p>
      Most data problems aren't really data problems — they're
      <em>agreement</em> problems. Two systems each hold perfectly good data
      but disagree on names, units, structure, or what "optional" means. Xeto's
      answer is to make the agreement itself a first-class, versioned artifact:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-ink">Specs are data.</strong> A spec is itself just
        a dict — you can query it, transform it, and generate code, docs, or
        UIs from it with the same tools you use on instance data.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-ink">Validation is built in.</strong> Constraints —
        types, units, enums, numeric ranges, required vs. maybe — live in the
        spec, so every consumer validates the same way.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-ink">Composition over duplication.</strong>
        Inheritance, mixins, and choices let libraries extend each other
        instead of copying definitions — <span class="font-mono">ph.points</span>
        builds on <span class="font-mono">ph</span> builds on
        <span class="font-mono">sys</span>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-ink">Docs come along for free.</strong> Every spec
        carries its documentation, so tooling like the explorer on this site
        can render a complete, browsable reference straight from source.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mt-12 text-xl font-semibold">Where xeto.dev fits in</h2>
  <div class="mt-4 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-ink-soft">
    <p>
      A spec language is only as valuable as the specs people share. That's
      what this site is for: <strong class="text-ink">xeto.dev is the
      distribution and community layer for Xeto</strong> — the place where
      libraries are published, versioned, browsed, and discovered.
    </p>
    <p>
      Just as npm did for JavaScript and crates.io did for Rust, the registry
      turns a language into an ecosystem: publish a library once, and anyone
      can pull it into their namespace, browse its specs in the
      <a href="/explorer/" class="text-brand underline decoration-brand-soft underline-offset-2">explorer</a>,
      and build on it in their own domain. Today that starts with the
      <a href="/libs" class="text-brand underline decoration-brand-soft underline-offset-2">core and Project Haystack libraries</a>
      — publishing for the community is where this is headed.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mt-12 text-xl font-semibold">Go deeper</h2>
  <div class="mt-5 mb-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
    <a href="/docs/lang" class="card-brand block">
      <h3 class="font-semibold">Language docs</h3>
      <p class="card-soft mt-1 text-sm">
        The complete reference, published from the doc.xeto library →
      </p>
    </a>
    <a href="/explorer/" class="card-brand block">
      <h3 class="font-semibold">The explorer</h3>
      <p class="card-soft mt-1 text-sm">
        Browse every spec in the registry, live →
      </p>
    </a>
    <a href="https://github.com/Project-Haystack/xeto" class="card-brand block">
      <h3 class="font-semibold">GitHub</h3>
      <p class="card-soft mt-1 text-sm">
        Source, core libraries, and issues →
      </p>
    </a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
